# Changelog - xcesppkg

## 0.3.20

- **OSPF-MIB::ospfNbrTable bridge** (RFC 4750) — per-VRF OSPFv2
  neighbor state polled via FRR vtysh and exposed via SNMP at
  `.1.3.6.1.2.1.14.10`.  Per-(router, vrf) SNMPv3 contexts wired
  on day one.  Bundles xcesp-on-rtr 0.2.11, xcespproc 0.2.11,
  xcespserver 0.3.20.
- **IPv4-only** — OSPFV3-MIB::ospfv3NbrTable for v6 deferred.

  ```
  snmpwalk -v2c -c <community> router 1.3.6.1.2.1.14.10
  snmpwalk -v3 ... -n "r=RC;v=default" router 1.3.6.1.2.1.14.10
  ```

## 0.3.19

- **Hotfix for 0.3.18 BGP4-MIB INDEX byte-reversal.**  Bundles
  xcespserver 0.3.19 (host-order uint32 fix for ASN_IPADDRESS
  index encoding).  Other versions unchanged.

## 0.3.18

- **BGP4-MIB::bgpPeerTable bridge** (RFC 4273) — per-VRF BGP peer
  state polled via FRR vtysh and exposed via SNMP at
  `.1.3.6.1.2.1.15.3`.  Per-(router, vrf) SNMPv3 contexts wired
  on day one.  Bundles xcesp-on-rtr 0.2.10, xcespproc 0.2.10,
  xcespserver 0.3.18.
- **IPv4-only** for this slot.  IPv6 BGP peers (BGP4V2-MIB)
  deferred to a follow-up.

  ```
  snmpwalk -v2c -c <community> router BGP4-MIB::bgpPeerState
  # or scoped:
  snmpwalk -v3 ... -n "r=RC;v=default" router BGP4-MIB::bgpPeerTable
  ```

## 0.3.17

- **Per-(router, vrf) SNMPv3 contexts for IP-MIB + IP-FORWARD-MIB.**
  Bundles xcespserver 0.3.17 (extends `buildContextReg()` to also
  register the 3 newer tables under each active context).  Other
  versions unchanged.

  Walk a scoped IP / route view per (router, vrf):
  ```
  snmpwalk -v3 -u test -l noAuthNoPriv -n "r=RC;v=default" localhost \
      IP-MIB::ipAddressTable
  snmpwalk -v3 -u test -l noAuthNoPriv -n "r=RC;v=default" localhost \
      IP-FORWARD-MIB::inetCidrRouteTable
  ```

## 0.3.16

- **Hotfix for 0.3.15: default-VRF routes weren't being polled.**
  Bundles xcesp-on-rtr 0.2.9 + xcespproc 0.2.9 with the fix.
  Other versions unchanged.

## 0.3.15

- **IP-FORWARD-MIB::inetCidrRouteTable bridge** (RFC 4292) — kernel
  routing table per (router, vrf) exposed via SNMP at
  `.1.3.6.1.2.1.4.24.7`.  Off-the-shelf NMS tools see one row per
  installed route across every (router, vrf) of the XCESP box,
  with ifIndex linking each row back to the same IF-MIB row.
  Sourced from `ip -j route show vrf <V>` polled per-VRF by
  xcesp-on-rtr.
- Bundles xcespserver 0.3.15, xcespcli 0.3.1, xcespproc 0.2.8,
  xcespwdog 0.2.0.

## 0.3.14

- **Mirror 0.3.13 MIB install in xcesp-activate** so a CLI
  `copy sw latest backup-sw` + `software-install` + reboot path
  also lands the updated XCESP-MIB.txt at `/usr/share/snmp/mibs/`.
  Without this, 0.3.13's install.sh fix only helped fresh installs
  (the CLI upgrade path never re-runs install.sh — same gotcha
  pattern as memory `project_cli_upgrade_self_sufficient`).

## 0.3.13

- **Install XCESP-MIB.txt system-wide** to `/usr/share/snmp/mibs/`
  during install.sh so `snmpwalk -m XCESP-MIB` (or any snmpwalk with
  `MIBS=ALL`) on the router resolves names without an operator scp.
  Only our private MIB is shipped — IETF standard MIBs (IF-MIB,
  IP-MIB, etc.) remain operator-installed via the distro path
  (`snmp-mibs-downloader` from Debian non-free, etc.); we don't ship
  those for licensing reasons.

## 0.3.12

- **Cleanup bundle.**  Bundles xcesp-on-rtr 0.2.7 + xcespproc 0.2.7
  to remove the temporary `addr_poll` debug log line introduced in
  0.3.10/0.3.11.  The 0.3.8 IP-MIB pipeline is verified end-to-end
  on Fedora (snmpwalk returns kernel addresses + ARP/NDP cache rows
  via the new RFC 4293 tables).

## 0.3.11

- Bundle xcesp-on-rtr 0.2.6 + xcespproc 0.2.6: unconditional
  `addr_poll` log line per monitor tick (no `ifaceUp` gate).  0.3.10
  produced zero log lines on the test VM, so we need to first prove
  whether `monitorLinkState()` reaches my code at all.

## 0.3.10

- **Diagnostic build for the 0.3.8 IP-MIB empty-rows bug.**  Bundles
  xcesp-on-rtr 0.2.5 + xcespproc 0.2.5 with a single per-iface
  `addr_poll dev=<X> addresses=N neighbours=M` INFO log per
  monitor tick.  Lets the next debugging round see directly whether
  the parser populates the address vector.  Once the actual fix
  ships, this log line will be removed.

## 0.3.9

- **0.3.8 IP-MIB hotfix.**  Bundles xcespserver 0.3.9 (off-by-one
  parts-count fix in the IP-MIB rescan: empty rows on every walk →
  now returns one row per kernel address / ARP-NDP cache entry as
  intended).  xcespcli 0.3.1, xcespproc 0.2.4, xcespwdog 0.2.0
  unchanged.

## 0.3.8

- **IP-MIB::ipAddressTable + ipNetToPhysicalTable bridges** (RFC 4293
  unified v4 + v6).  Off-the-shelf SNMP NMS tools (LibreNMS, Zabbix,
  Observium, PRTG) that walk the standard `.1.3.6.1.2.1.4.34` and
  `.1.3.6.1.2.1.4.35` tables now see one row per kernel address and
  ARP/NDP cache entry across every (router, vrf, interface) of the
  XCESP box, with ifIndex linking each row back to the matching
  IF-MIB / xcespIfTable row.  Sourced from `ip -j addr show` and
  `ip -j neigh show` polled per-iface by xcesp-on-rtr.
- Bundles xcespserver 0.3.8, xcespcli 0.3.1, xcespproc 0.2.4,
  xcespwdog 0.2.0.

## 0.3.7

- **SNMPv3 trap + inform delivery via USM** + per-trap
  contextName tagging (Approach A).  Bundles xcespserver 0.3.7,
  xcespcli 0.3.1, xcespproc 0.2.3, xcespwdog 0.2.0.
- **Operator UX**:
  ```
  > management snmp
  >   trap-target nms-v3-primary
  >     host 10.0.0.51
  >     version v3
  >     auth-protocol SHA-256
  >     auth-password mySecretAuth
  >     priv-protocol AES-256
  >     priv-password mySecretPriv
  >     security-level authPriv
  >     inform true              ; true=acked Inform-Request (default), false=fire-and-forget Trap
  >   !
  > !
  > commit ; save
  ```
- **xcesp-activate** now renders one `trapsess` line per
  enabled v3 trap-target into the existing
  `# BEGIN xcesp-snmp` marker block.  Argument mapping:
  - `-v 3 -u <label>` (label is the USM username on the remote)
  - `-l noAuthNoPriv|authNoPriv|authPriv` (auto-derived if a
    password is missing for the requested level)
  - `-a/-A` auth proto + password (if level ≥ auth)
  - `-x/-X` priv proto + password (if level == priv)
  - `-Ci` inform flag (when `inform = true`)
  - `-e <engine-id>` if operator pre-shared one
  - `<host>:<port>` destination
- v1 destinations still use `trapsink`; v2c destinations still
  use `trap2sink` — only v3 destinations get the `trapsess`
  treatment.
- **Approach A — context-tagged trap PDUs.** Trap origins
  carry their source `(router, vrf)` contextName in the
  trap PDU's scopedPDU header.  SNMPv3 receivers can
  filter on `snmpTrapContext` natively; v1/v2c receivers
  silently ignore the field.  Free upgrade — no operator
  config required.

## 0.3.6

- **Fix: xcesp uid couldn't reach /var/agentx/master on Debian.**
  Debian's snmpd creates `/var/agentx/` as `drwx------ root:root`
  (mode 0700) — restrictive enough that the `xcesp` group can't
  even traverse the directory to reach the socket inside it.
  Even though our `ExecStartPost` correctly set the socket's own
  group to `xcesp` and mode to 0660, the parent directory blocked
  access.  Symptom on Debian: xcespserver journal full of
  `Warning: Failed to connect to the agentx master agent
  (/var/agentx/master)` — repeated every 15 s.  Consequence:
  AgentX subagent never registered, snmpd served its built-in
  mibII/interfaces module instead of XCESP's IF-MIB handlers
  (operator saw host NICs in walks instead of XCESP's
  `router R vrf V interface I` names).
- **Fix**: `ExecStartPost` now chgrps + chmods the parent
  directory `/var/agentx` to `xcesp:xcesp 0750` in addition to
  the existing socket fix.  Defensive `+` prefix added so the
  command always runs as root regardless of future snmpd-unit
  hardening.
- **Roadmap shift**: SNMPv3 trap delivery (was 0.3.6) → 0.3.7;
  downstream slots shift +1.  Pure bash patch in xcesp-activate.

## 0.3.5

- **Fix: 0.3.3 → 0.3.4 migration silently skipped Phase B.**  The
  hash-sidecar idempotency optimisation in 0.3.3 correctly
  detects "no changes since last activation" by hashing the
  desired (name, protocols, passwords) tuple.  But when 0.3.4
  changed the chosen persistent-state file path (Fedora
  /var/lib/net-snmp/snmpd.conf → Debian /var/lib/snmp/snmpd.conf),
  the hash WAS unchanged and Phase B was skipped — leaving the
  stale createUser block in the wrong file and no usmUser
  entries on the correct one.  Operator hit it on a Debian VM
  during 0.3.x verification 2026-06-16.
- **Fix**: xcesp-activate now strips any stale
  `# BEGIN xcesp-v3-users` block from the non-chosen candidate
  path on every activation, AND forces Phase B to re-run when it
  finds one.  Covers the upgrade scenario automatically — no
  operator workaround needed.
- **Roadmap shift**: SNMPv3 trap delivery (was 0.3.5) → 0.3.6;
  downstream slots shift +1.  No xcespserver / xcespcli /
  xcespproc / xcespwdog source changes in 0.3.5 — pure bash
  patch in xcesp-activate.

## 0.3.4

- **Fix: xcesp-activate hardcoded the Fedora net-snmp persistent
  path** (`/var/lib/net-snmp/snmpd.conf`).  On Debian, the snmpd
  package's runtime daemon reads from `/var/lib/snmp/snmpd.conf`
  (owned by `Debian-snmp` user), so the Phase B `createUser`
  block we wrote never got consumed → SNMPv3 users never made it
  into snmpd's USM database → `snmpwalk -v3` failed with
  `Unknown user name` on Debian even when 0.3.3 looked correct
  on Fedora.
- **Fix**: xcesp-activate now probes both candidate paths and
  uses whichever snmpd actually reads from on this distro.
  Probe order: existing `snmpd.conf` file → existing directory →
  /etc/os-release-based fallback (`/var/lib/snmp` for
  debian/ubuntu, `/var/lib/net-snmp` otherwise).  Ownership of
  the persistent file is preserved when it exists; new files
  inherit the parent directory's owner so Debian's
  `Debian-snmp:Debian-snmp` and Fedora's `root:root` conventions
  both hold.
- **Teardown** path also probes both locations and strips any
  xcesp-managed createUser block found in either.
- **Roadmap shift**: SNMPv3 trap delivery (was 0.3.4) → 0.3.5.
  Everything downstream shifts +1.

## 0.3.3

- **SNMPv3 USM users via CLI — last `management/` feature now
  CLI-managed.**  Bundles xcespserver 0.3.3, xcespcli 0.3.1,
  xcespproc 0.2.3, xcespwdog 0.2.0.
- **Operator UX:**
  ```
  > management snmp
  >   enabled true
  >   v3-user xcesp-ro
  >     auth-password mySecretAuth123
  >     priv-password mySecretPriv123
  >   !
  >   v3-user xcesp-rw-bgp
  >     auth-protocol SHA-256
  >     auth-password ...
  >     priv-protocol AES-256
  >     priv-password ...
  >     access rw
  >     view bgp-only
  >   !
  > !
  > commit ; save
  ```
- **xcesp-activate two-phase materialisation:**
  - **Phase A** renders `rouser`/`rwuser` lines into the existing
    `# BEGIN xcesp-snmp` marker block in `/etc/snmp/snmpd.conf`,
    alongside view + community + trap-target lines.  Security
    level derived from password presence
    (`noauth` / `auth` / `priv`).  Required `-V VIEW` literal
    syntax baked in (same as 0.3.1 v2c-community writer).
  - **Phase B** handles the `createUser` consume-on-start dance:
    hash the desired `(name, protocols, passwords)` tuple,
    compare against `/var/lib/xcesp/snmp-v3-users.state`.  On
    mismatch: stop snmpd, append managed-block `createUser`
    lines to `/var/lib/net-snmp/snmpd.conf`, save new hash,
    force restart.  On match: skip the dance entirely.  Result:
    snmpd is only restarted on actual v3-user changes.
- **Teardown**: when SNMP is disabled, the xcesp-managed
  `createUser` block is stripped from
  `/var/lib/net-snmp/snmpd.conf` and the hash sidecar is
  removed.  snmpd is restarted to drop the managed users.
- **Roadmap position**: last security-side feature.  Next is
  **0.3.4 SNMPv3 trap delivery via USM** (extends trap-target
  with `auth-protocol`, `priv-protocol`, `inform`, etc.).

## 0.3.2

- **0.3.1 follow-up — `xcespview` auto-default hole fix.**  Bundles
  xcespserver 0.3.2, xcespcli 0.3.1, xcespproc 0.2.3,
  xcespwdog 0.2.0.
- 0.3.1's `ManagementConfig` auto-inserted the default
  `xcespview included .1` only when the operator's views list was
  empty.  An operator who defined `view bgp-only` (or any other
  named view) without redefining `xcespview` ended up with v2c
  communities defaulting to `view xcespview` referencing a
  non-existent view — snmpd silently granted them zero access.
- xcespserver 0.3.2 changes the condition to "auto-insert when no
  view named `xcespview` is present in the list".  Operator-defined
  `view xcespview` blocks still win (no auto-add when the label is
  there).
- **Roadmap shift**: v3-user CLI was previously slated for 0.3.2.
  It moves to **0.3.3**; everything downstream shifts +1.

## 0.3.1

- **SNMPv2c community-string CLI + shared `view` schema +
  `show server` secret-encryption indicator.**  Bundles
  xcespserver 0.3.1, xcespcli 0.3.1, xcespproc 0.2.3,
  xcespwdog 0.2.0.
- **Operator UX:**
  ```
  > management snmp
  >   enabled true
  >   view bgp-only
  >     included .1.3.6.1.2.1.15
  >   !
  >   v2c-community legacy-ro
  >     community publicReadOnly12345
  >     source 10.0.0.0/8
  >   !
  >   v2c-community ops-write
  >     community write-secret-7777
  >     access rw
  >     view bgp-only
  >   !
  > !
  > commit ; save
  ```
  Communities encrypted at rest via SecretEncryptor (inherits
  0.3.0 fleet-key portability automatically).
- **xcesp-activate** renders view definitions FIRST inside the
  existing `# BEGIN xcesp-snmp` marker block, then community
  lines that reference them.  Required `-V VIEW` literal flag
  baked in from day one (the bare-view-name form errors out with
  `bad SUBTREE object id` in net-snmp; bit us during the 0.2.32
  manual setup recipe).  Inline `#` comments after directive
  lines are also avoided.
- **Shared view schema** is the same one 0.3.2 v3-user will
  consume.  ManagementConfig auto-inserts a default
  `view xcespview included .1` when the operator hasn't defined
  any views (zero-config still works).
- **`show server`** now shows the active SecretEncryptor source
  inline (no log grep required to see it).
- Both v2c communities and v3 users (when 0.3.2 lands) will share
  the same view definitions — no parallel view schemas.

## 0.3.0

- **Cross-machine secret portability — opens the 0.3.x line.**
  Bundles xcespserver 0.3.0, xcespcli 0.2.9, xcespproc 0.2.3,
  xcespwdog 0.2.0.
- **`[SECRETS] KEY_SOURCE` in `xcespserver.ini`** (default
  `machine-id` — 0.2.x behaviour byte-for-byte).  Operators opt
  into fleet portability by provisioning
  `/etc/xcesp/fleet.key` (32+ bytes, mode 0640 root:xcesp,
  via Ansible vault / ZTP / scp) and flipping the knob to
  `file:/etc/xcesp/fleet.key,machine-id`.  Once the file is in
  place on every fleet router, `show running-config` output
  pastes verbatim across the fleet — secrets decrypt natively
  on the target, RMA recovery works, Ansible templating with
  secrets becomes possible.
- **install.sh non-destructive** — existing remote
  `xcespserver.ini` files are preserved as before; only fresh
  installs pick up the new `[SECRETS]` block.
- **`xcesp-activate` fleet.key sanity** — if
  `/etc/xcesp/fleet.key` is present, enforce mode 0640 +
  ownership root:xcesp on every activation.  Warn if the file is
  empty (`SecretEncryptor` rejects zero-byte sources to avoid the
  constant-key footgun on freshly-cloned VMs).  Does NOT create
  or sync the file — operators provision out-of-band.
- **Lands FIRST in 0.3.x** so the v2c-community (0.3.1), v3-user
  (0.3.2), and v3-trap (0.3.3) secrets coming next all inherit
  portable encryption from day one.

## 0.2.33

- **SNMPv3 contexts — per-router-any-VRF aggregates.**  Bundles
  xcespserver 0.2.20, xcespcli 0.2.9, xcespproc 0.2.3,
  xcespwdog 0.2.0.
- `management/snmp/if-context-format` now accepts a
  whitespace-separated list of templates so an operator can register
  multiple parallel context shapes from one knob.  Each template's
  placeholders determine the filter scope — omitting `%V` means
  "any VRF", omitting `%R` means "any router".
  ```
  > management snmp
  >   if-context-format "r=%R;v=%V r=%R"
  > !
  > commit ; save
  ```
  Both walks then work side by side:
  ```
  snmpwalk -v3 ... -n "r=RC;v=default" router IF-MIB::ifDescr   # exact
  snmpwalk -v3 ... -n "r=RC"           router IF-MIB::ifDescr   # any VRF
  ```
- See xcespserver 0.2.20 CHANGELOG for registration + iterator
  filter details.

## 0.2.32

- **SNMP polish: trap-target CLI + tri-state DISPATCHER + SNMPv3
  contexts.**  Bundles xcespserver 0.2.19, xcespcli 0.2.9,
  xcespproc 0.2.3, xcespwdog 0.2.0.
- **CLI trap-target.**
  ```
  > management snmp
  >   enabled true
  >   trap-target nms-primary
  >     host 10.0.0.51
  >     community publictrap
  >   !
  >   trap-target nms-backup
  >     host 10.0.0.52
  >     port 1162
  >   !
  > !
  > commit ; save
  ```
  `xcesp-activate` reads the materialised list from
  `/var/lib/xcesp/aaa-config.state` and writes one
  `trap2sink` (v2c) / `trapsink` (v1) line per enabled target
  into the existing `# BEGIN xcesp-snmp` marker block in
  `/etc/snmp/snmpd.conf`.  Restarts snmpd on any change.
- **Bundled INI default** now `DISPATCHER = AUTO` (was `LOG`).
  Tri-state behaviour: `AUTO` picks SNMP iff trap-targets are
  configured; `LOG` and `SNMP` keep the explicit-override
  paths.  Existing remote `xcespserver.ini` files are
  preserved by install.sh's non-destructive policy.
- **SNMPv3 contexts** auto-registered per (router, vrf).
  Pollers do `snmpwalk -v3 -n "r=HA;v=WAN" …` and see only
  that VRF's slice of the three iterator tables.  Default-
  context (flat) registration unchanged for stock NMS tools
  that don't speak contexts.
- See xcespserver 0.2.19 CHANGELOG for handler / parser /
  registration details.

## 0.2.31

- **SNMP linkUp/linkDown traps + IF-MIB::ifLastChange.** Bundles
  xcespserver 0.2.18, xcespcli 0.2.9, xcespproc 0.2.3,
  xcespwdog 0.2.0.
- IF-MIB::linkUp / linkDown fire on interface oper-status
  transitions (driven by xcesp-on-rtr's existing LOS alarm).
  Operator opts in via `[EVENTS] DISPATCHER = SNMP` in
  xcespserver.ini; otherwise events go to the log dispatcher.
  Trap destinations stay operator-managed in
  `/etc/snmp/snmpd.conf` (trap2sink).
- IF-MIB::ifLastChange now returns real TimeTicks since agent boot
  at the moment the interface entered its current operStatus
  (previously hardcoded 0).  xcesp-on-rtr emits CLOCK_MONOTONIC ms
  of each transition; xcespserver subtracts its own start anchor
  and converts to 1/100 s units.
- See xcespserver 0.2.18 and xcesp-on-rtr 0.2.3 CHANGELOG entries
  for handler / emission details.

## 0.2.30

- **SNMP interface counters.**  Bundles xcespserver 0.2.17,
  xcespcli 0.2.9, xcespproc 0.2.2, xcespwdog 0.2.0.
- IF-MIB::ifTable now reports `ifIn{Octets,UcastPkts,Discards,Errors}`
  and `ifOut*` mirrors as 32-bit Counter32 columns.
- IF-MIB::ifXTable is freshly registered, exposing 64-bit
  `ifHC{In,Out}{Octets,UcastPkts}` Counter64 columns plus `ifName`
  (`<router>:<vrf>:<iface>`) and `ifHighSpeed` (Mbps).  HC variants
  let NMS pollers track high-rate counters without 32-bit wrap.
- xcesp-on-rtr now reads `stats64` from `ip -j -s link show` every
  monitorLinkState() tick (~5 s) and emits eight counter ServerStatus
  keys per interface.
- See xcespserver 0.2.17 and xcesp-on-rtr 0.2.2 CHANGELOG entries for
  handler / emission details.

## 0.2.29

- **Hotfix to 0.2.28: bundle the actually-rebuilt xcespproc 0.2.1.**
  0.2.28 shipped xcespproc 0.2.0 — the byte-identical 0.2.x baseline,
  linked against the pre-emission xcesp-on-rtr.  In running stacks
  SnmpAgent's new ifType/ifPhysAddress/xcespIfType column handlers
  fell back to placeholders (`propVirtual(53)`, empty OCTET STRING,
  `"unknown"`) because xcespproc never produced the underlying
  `admin-status` / `interface-type` / `mac-address` ServerStatus
  keys.  Pure relink — no xcespproc source changes.
- Bundles xcespserver 0.2.16, xcespcli 0.2.9, xcespproc 0.2.1,
  xcespwdog 0.2.0.

## 0.2.28

- Bundles xcespserver 0.2.16, xcespcli 0.2.9, xcespproc 0.2.0,
  xcespwdog 0.2.0 with the SnmpAgent column-handler refresh — the
  IF-MIB columns `ifAdminStatus`, `ifPhysAddress`, `ifType` now return
  real per-interface values instead of the 0.2.22-era placeholders,
  and the private `xcespIfType` column carries the raw XCESP type
  string.  Backed by new `admin-status` / `interface-type` /
  `mac-address` status emissions from xcesp-on-rtr 0.2.1.
- See the xcespserver 0.2.16 and xcesp-on-rtr 0.2.1 CHANGELOG entries
  for handler / emission details.

## 0.2.27

- **Fix: snmpget / snmpwalk on `IF-MIB::ifTable` columns crashed
  xcespserver.**  Bundles xcespserver 0.2.15.  The 0.2.11 iterator's
  `data_context` was a pointer into the iterator's vector buffer;
  net-snmp's table_iterator helper disposed of the loop_context
  before the column handler ran, so the column handler dereferenced
  freed memory and segfaulted on the first GET.  Symptom: subagent
  disconnected silently after one request, subsequent snmpwalks
  served from snmpd's built-in IF-MIB instead.

  Now allocates a heap copy of each row's `Entry` and pairs it
  with a `free_data_context` callback for clean per-row lifetime
  management.

  Verified end-to-end on xcesptest local stack:
  `IF-MIB::ifTable` and `XCESP-MIB::xcespIfTable` walks both return
  the configured XCESP interfaces; xcespserver stays alive across
  consecutive walks.

