## 0.1.131

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.34, xcespcli 0.1.32, xcespproc 0.1.74, xcespwdog
  unchanged.  Pulls in xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.211 (dhcrelay iface-ready gate +
  shorter post-launch grace) via xcespproc.
- **scripts/xcesp-activate: chmod /var/lib/dhcp to 0775 (was 0755).**
  ISC dhclient runs in the SELinux `dhcpc_t` domain on Fedora, which is
  denied `CAP_DAC_OVERRIDE`.  With 0755 the euid=0 process cannot bypass
  the directory-perm check when neither uid nor gid matches the owner;
  fsgid is inherited from xcespproc (the xcesp user), so group-writable
  lets dhclient create the lease via group perms with no dac_override
  needed.  Symptom of 0755 on Fedora: dhclient logs "can't create
  /var/lib/dhcp/...: Permission denied", binds the lease in memory (DHCP
  still functions), but the on-disk lease file never appears — which
  surfaced as XCESPQA NETSVC chapter 1 tests 1.3 / 1.6 and chapter 4
  tests 4.1 / 4.2 failing.

## 0.1.130

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.34, xcespcli 0.1.32, xcespproc 0.1.73,
  xcespwdog 0.1.4.
- **New CLI command: `show log [pre N] [filter STRING]`.**  Streams
  `tail -n N -F /var/xcesp/log/xcesp.log` (optionally piped through
  `grep -F --line-buffered -e FILTER`) to the operator's terminal
  until Ctrl+C.  Server-mediated streaming — works the same way
  over Unix-socket and TCP, even when the operator's host has no
  read access to `/var/xcesp/log/`.  Reuses the PTY-based async
  plumbing built for `file-copy STREAMING=1`.
- x86_64 only — ARM64 to follow when the build host is back.

## 0.1.129

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.33, xcespcli 0.1.31, xcespproc 0.1.73,
  xcespwdog 0.1.4.
- **IPsec PSK encryption-at-rest re-enabled** (xcespserver 0.1.33).
  The SecretEncryptor rule for `ipsec / secret <NAME> / secret <VAL>`
  was written when `ipsec` was a top-level node; after the schema
  refactor put `ipsec` under `router`, the matcher's greedy
  router-push for the other router-prefixed rules (dot1x, ntp)
  consumed the stack before ipsec could be pushed.  Result: PSKs
  silently stored as plaintext.  Rule path updated to
  `[router, ipsec, secret]`.
- x86_64 only — ARM64 to follow when the build host is back.

## 0.1.128

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.32, xcespcli 0.1.31, xcespproc 0.1.73,
  xcespwdog 0.1.4.
- **`reboot` / `reboot light` / `software-install` actually work
  now**.  Three issues stacked on top of each other:
  - The CLI completer never offered `reboot light` because the
    branch was guarded by `typedTokens.empty()` (always false here).
    Fixed in xcespcli 0.1.31.
  - `xcesp-activate` did not write a sudoers rule for the
    `systemctl restart xcesp` / `systemctl reboot` commands that
    `doReboot()` invokes — sudo silently refused, the action
    completed "successfully" with no follow-through.  Added a new
    `/etc/sudoers.d/xcesp-reboot` granting xcesp NOPASSWD for those
    exact commands.
  - `FileActionHandler::doReboot()` now surfaces sudo failures
    instead of returning a misleading "restart initiated" (xcespserver
    0.1.32) — so a future missing-sudo regression fails loudly.
  - `software-install` was already swapping mainsw ↔ backupsw
    correctly; what looked like "installation does nothing" was
    actually the *follow-up* reboot failing.  With the reboot path
    fixed, the swap-then-reboot flow completes end-to-end.
- x86_64 only — ARM64 to follow when the build host is back.

## 0.1.127

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.31, xcespcli 0.1.30, xcespproc 0.1.73,
  xcespwdog 0.1.4.
- **Random xcespproc kills root-caused and fixed.**  Diagnostic
  output in 0.1.126 confirmed: each killed xcesproc received exactly
  ONE SIGUSR1 (the very first one, at +10s), then never another
  before the `lastHB + 180s` deadline fired.  Root cause: SIGUSR1 is
  a STANDARD signal — when eight xcesproc children all hit their
  first `checkWatchdogs()` tick within microseconds of each other
  and all `kill(getppid(), SIGUSR1)`, Linux coalesces the pending
  signal and only ONE delivery reaches the wdog per storm.  The
  unlucky seven xcesprocs' `lastHB` is never updated, the wdog
  thinks they're hung, and SIGKILLs them when the deadline expires.
  Fix: parent heartbeat now uses **SIGRTMIN+1** (real-time signal,
  queued per-sender, never coalesced) — every child's heartbeat
  reaches the wdog regardless of arrival order.  evapplication 0.0.9.
- x86_64 only — ARM64 to follow when the build host is back.

## 0.1.126

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.30, xcespcli 0.1.30, xcespproc 0.1.72,
  xcespwdog 0.1.3.
- **xcespwdog 0.1.3 diagnostic logging** for the random-instance kill
  investigation on the Fedora VM: `Launched: …` now reports the
  applied timer values (`start=Nms interval=Nms`), and the
  `Watchdog killed …` line appends the exact timer state at kill
  time (`[pid=… now=… lastHB=… startMs=… startTimeout=…
  intervalTimeout=… deadline=…]`).  This will tell us in one line
  whether `lastHB` is being updated by SIGUSR1 from the child or
  not, and which deadline-arithmetic branch fired.
- x86_64 only — ARM64 to follow when the build host is back.

## 0.1.125

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.30, xcespcli 0.1.30, xcespproc 0.1.72,
  xcespwdog 0.1.2.
- **`xcesp-activate`: hostapd + wpa_supplicant now setuid-root**, not
  file-caps.  Same fix we applied to charon in 0.1.72.  Symptom on
  Fedora: `bind: Permission denied` from PF_PACKET even with all the
  right boxes ticked — `cap_net_admin,cap_net_raw=ep` on the
  binary (verified via `getcap`), `NoNewPrivs: 0` (verified via
  `/proc/self/status`), SELinux Permissive, no AVCs, no cgroup-BPF
  filters.  Confirmed by running the exact same command as root —
  works.  Conclusion: Fedora's kernel silently refuses to activate
  non-root file-caps on these daemons.  Setuid-root sidesteps the
  whole question — uid elevates on exec, kernel grants full caps
  unconditionally, hostapd/wpa_supplicant drop privileges internally
  once their wired driver opens the PF_PACKET socket.
- x86_64 only — ARM64 to follow when the build host is back.

## 0.1.124

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.30, xcespcli 0.1.30, xcespproc 0.1.72,
  xcespwdog 0.1.2.
- **dot1x launch-race fix** (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.210): RtrDot1xAuth +
  RtrDot1xSup now wait for their bound iface to reach operstate
  UP/UNKNOWN before spawning hostapd/wpa_supplicant.  Without it,
  both daemons launched in the same tick the rlink veth pair was
  being created, the wired driver got `SIOCGIFINDEX: No such device`
  and exited, and the supervisor's retry never caught up because
  every subsequent tick hit the same window on the Fedora VM.
- x86_64 only — ARM64 to follow when the build host is back.

## 0.1.123

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.30, xcespcli 0.1.30, xcespproc 0.1.71,
  xcespwdog 0.1.2.
- **Fedora hostapd `bind: Permission denied` fixed** (xcesp-on-rtr
  0.0.209).  Root cause: launching hostapd via `ip netns exec`
  chained through `/bin/sh → ip → hostapd`, and `ip` carries
  file caps, which clears the ambient cap set per capabilities(7).
  hostapd then bound PF_PACKET with no caps → EPERM.  Fixed by
  doing `setns()` in xcespproc's grandchild directly and exec'ing
  hostapd / wpa_supplicant without the `ip netns exec` prefix —
  ambient survives end-to-end.  Same idiom as the existing
  `execInNs` / `launchCharonInNs` paths.
- `xcespwdog` 0.1.2: kill / respawn / exit log lines now include
  the full child argv (`-i 8` etc.) so operators can see *which*
  xcespproc instance got killed.
- x86_64 only — ARM64 to follow when the build host is back.

