## 0.1.112

- Same binaries as 0.1.110 / 0.1.111.  Single `xcesp-activate` fix.

- **AppArmor local override for chronyd (Debian/Ubuntu).**  The
  distro-shipped chronyd profile allows reading `/etc/chrony/*` and
  writing `/var/lib/chrony/*` but knows nothing about our per-
  namespace runtime path `/run/xcesp/ntp/<ns>/chrony.conf`.  Without
  a local override, chronyd dies at startup with `Fatal error: Could
  not open /run/xcesp/ntp/<ns>/chrony.conf : Permission denied` and
  the supervisor respawn-loops indefinitely.  We now call
  `apply_apparmor_local /usr/sbin/chronyd` so the same `/var/lib/xcesp/**
  rwk, /run/xcesp/** rwk,` lines we drop for dhclient also extend the
  chronyd profile.  No-op on SELinux-only / no-AppArmor systems.

## 0.1.111

- Same binaries as 0.1.110.  Single `xcesp-activate` fix.

- **chronyd file caps**: `setcap cap_net_bind_service,cap_net_raw=ep
  /usr/sbin/chronyd` (and the other distro paths).  xcespproc raises
  `cap_net_bind_service` via ambient before exec, but chronyd does
  `setuid(chrony)` early in startup and on some distros the cap path
  is lost across that setuid — chronyd then logs `Could not open NTP
  socket on X.X.X.X:123` / `Could not open command socket on
  127.0.0.1:323` and the daemon runs broken (no NTP service, no
  control socket for chronyc).  Seen in production on Fedora 41 with
  chrony 4.6.1.  File caps on the binary always work.  Apply non-
  destructively (skip if already capped).

## 0.1.110

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.29, xcespcli 0.1.26, xcespproc 0.1.54,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 with xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.192.

- **RtrNtp: pure NTP-server routers now actually launch chronyd.**
  The 0.1.109 `wantRunning` gate required at least one upstream
  `ntp-source`, so server-only topologies (`ntp-server true` plus
  interface bindings, no upstream sources) silently nopped — chronyd
  never started, no bindaddress emitted, LAN clients got no
  responses.  Was caught by the new Ch06 NTP QA chapter.

## 0.1.109

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.29, xcespcli 0.1.26, xcespproc 0.1.53,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 with xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.191.

- **NTP symmetric-key authentication (optional).**  Three new attrs on
  the `ntp` parent and three on each `ntp-source` enable HMAC-based
  authentication between an xcesp NTP server and its clients, or
  between an xcesp NTP client and its upstreams.  Plain operation
  remains the default; existing configs are unaffected.
  - Downstream key is router-wide (one key id+secret offered to all
    LAN clients).
  - Per-upstream key allows the same router to authenticate against
    multiple servers under different credentials.
  - Algorithm enum: `MD5`, `SHA1`, `SHA256`, `SHA384`, `SHA512`,
    `AES128`, `AES256`. Default `SHA256`.
  - Secrets are encoded at rest in `show running-config` (`${enc:v1:…}`
    marker, same mechanism as IPsec PSK).  Chrony's keyfile on disk is
    written with the plaintext form (mode 0600).
  - All-or-none triple validation at commit.

- xcespproc diagnostic logs (DEBUG/WARNING) for main-loop drift and
  slow callbacks — see xcespproc 0.1.53 CHANGELOG.

## 0.1.108

- Same binaries as 0.1.106 / 0.1.107.  Single `xcesp-activate` fix.

- **chown `/var/lib/dhcp` to the xcesp uid.**  Without this, the
  directory stays `root:root 755` from `mkdir -p`.  xcespproc runs as
  the xcesp uid and the `firstLaunch_` lease wipe in
  `RtrDhcpClient::startDhclient()` silently `unlink()`'s with EACCES.
  dhclient then launches with a stale lease, enters INIT-REBOOT,
  unicasts DHCPREQUEST to the cached server-id — which after a
  netns recreate no longer answers — and stays bound to a dead
  lease in memory.  Visible symptom: in Fedora/Debian production
  VMs, RE never sends a fresh DISCOVER through the relay even
  though all the daemons are running.  dhclient is setuid root so
  it still creates files in the directory after the chown.  ARM64
  dnfv was unaffected because xcespproc runs as root there.

## 0.1.107

- Same binaries as 0.1.106 (xcespserver 0.1.28, xcespcli 0.1.26,
  xcespproc 0.1.52, xcespwdog 0.1.1; xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.190).  Two
  `xcesp-activate` fixes only.

- **SELinux: relabel `/var/lib/dhcp` as `dhcpc_state_t`.**  ISC
  dhclient runs in `dhcpc_t` on Fedora and must write its lease file
  (`/var/lib/dhcp/dhclient-xcesp-<ns>-<dev>-v4.leases`) into a
  `dhcpc_state_t`-labeled directory.  The distro default for that
  path is `dhcp_state_t` (server-side); `mkdir -p` without
  `restorecon` leaves it `var_lib_t`.  Either label denies `dhcpc_t`
  from creating files there → dhclient logs `can't create
  ...leases: Permission denied`, binds the lease in memory (functional
  DHCP still works), but the on-disk record never persists.  `xcesp-
  activate` now runs `semanage fcontext -a -t dhcpc_state_t` on the
  whole subtree and `restorecon -R` so subsequent writes succeed.
  No-op on AppArmor / SELinux-disabled systems.

- **Bootstrap xcespwdog_proc.ini timers match the xcespserver formula.**
  Previously the bootstrap (written before xcespserver gets a chance
  to regenerate it) used `-s 30` heartbeat with `WDOG_START_TIMER=60000`.
  Production xcespserver computes timers as `heartbeatS * 1500` for
  start and `* 2` for interval.  When the initial CtrlLink DEPLOY
  callback at stack-start runs long, xcespproc's main event loop can
  delay the first SIGUSR1 past the tight 60s deadline → wdog kills
  xcespproc → dhcrelay/dhclient supervised by xcespproc lose ~25s of
  supervisor cycle.  Bootstrap now uses `-s 60` with `WDOG_START_TIMER
  =90000` and `WDOG_INTERVAL_TIMER=180000` — the same values
  xcespserver later writes to the generated proc.ini.

- ARM64 tarball deferred — build host still offline.  Will publish
  as a follow-up release asset.

## 0.1.106

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.28, xcespcli 0.1.26, xcespproc 0.1.52,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 — picks up xcespconfig 0.1.3 (nested-node
  validator recursion).
- **Per-nested-node `*.validate.py` hooks now actually run.**  Since
  the hooks framework was first introduced, `XCespConfig::validateHooks()`
  iterated only top-level nodes — so the `<nodetype>.validate.py`
  scripts for `interface`, `nat-snat`, `nat-dnat`, `qos-dscp-to-cos`,
  `qos-8021p-to-cos`, `qos-exp-to-cos`, `qos-queue-profile` were dead
  code on real configs (none of those types are ever top-level).  In
  practice this meant cross-attribute checks the schema couldn't
  express were silently ignored.  Examples now enforced at commit:
  * DHCP-server pool must fall inside one of the iface's configured
    IPv4 prefixes (and remote-subnet pools must lie inside their
    declared prefix).
  * SNAT `snat-address` and `snat-interface` are mutually exclusive.
  * QoS queue `cos-list` entries cannot overlap across queues; `wrr`
    requires `scheduler-weight`; queue ids must be contiguous 0..N-1.
  * Interface `phy-managed=true` and `unmanaged-address=true` require
    `type=device`.
  Dry-run against the IPsec, NAT, and DHCP scenario configs confirmed
  no realistic existing config is wrongly rejected by the newly-
  enabled scripts.

## 0.1.105

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.27, xcespcli 0.1.25, xcespproc 0.1.52,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 — picks up xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.190.
- **DHCP client now learns the default gateway from option 3.**
  `xcesp-dhclient-script` was previously a "address-only" callback by
  design — the default route was left to the (non-existent) RtrRoute
  hand-off path.  On BOUND/RENEW/REBIND/REBOOT it now installs
  `default via <gw> dev <iface> proto dhcp` from `new_routers`, and
  on EXPIRE/FAIL/RELEASE/STOP/TIMEOUT flushes only proto-dhcp routes
  through the iface — operator-static defaults are not touched.
  Limitation: DHCP option 6 (DNS) is still **not** applied, since
  dhclient drops the script to a non-root uid and `/etc/resolv.conf`
  needs a separate setuid helper (deferred — see the limitation
  callout in the router-guide and router-ref DHCP pages).
- **DHCP client wipes stale lease files on first launch each xcesp
  run** (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.190).  Forces a clean DISCOVER cycle every
  boot; eliminates the INIT-REBOOT silent-stall window where dhclient
  retries DHCPREQUEST against a moved/reset server for up to 60s
  before falling back to DISCOVER.

## 0.1.104

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.27, xcespcli 0.1.25, xcespproc 0.1.51,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 — picks up xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.189.
- **DHCP-client end-to-end fix.**  RtrInterface's address-sync routine
  used `IpCmd::parseAddrList()` which included DHCP/SLAAC-managed
  dynamic addresses.  On every tick after dhclient bound a lease,
  RtrInterface saw the leased IP as "not in config" and `ip addr
  del`'d it.  Visible symptom: DHCP server logs the lease ACTIVE for
  the client's MAC and the relay forwards the OFFER cleanly, but the
  client iface stays without an IPv4 address indefinitely.  Now
  `parseAddrList()` filters lines tagged ` dynamic`, so the
  syncAddresses comparison only operates on the static-address subset
  xcesp itself owns.

## 0.1.103

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.27, xcespcli 0.1.25, xcespproc 0.1.50,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 — picks up xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.188.
- **SNAT now works for TCP/UDP, not just ICMP.**  PAT-mode iptables
  rules previously emitted `--to-source IP:LO:HI` (colon between LO
  and HI), but iptables expects `IP:LO-HI`.  TCP and UDP SNAT rules
  silently failed with "Bad argument 1024:65535" while ICMP (no port
  range) worked, producing the confusing "ping out passes, DNS/HTTP
  out fails" pattern.  Fixed in RtrNatSnat's `buildRules()`.
- **Validators are now indent-style agnostic.**  Eight `*.validate.py`
  hooks hard-coded a 2-space indent stride between nesting levels.
  A config rendered or hand-edited with 4-space or tab indents had its
  attribute checks silently skipped — most visibly, the `nat-snat`
  mutex between `snat-address` and `snat-interface` never fired on
  non-2-space configs.  Each hook now pins the opener's exact leading-
  whitespace string for closer matching and discovers any deeper-block
  indent from the first body line.
- **DHCP-relay auto-upstream log noise removed.**  The 0.1.102
  upstream-iface auto-detect ran inside every supervisor tick and
  logged "auto-added upstream iface ..." each pass.  Now logs only
  on first add and on actual change (route flip / HA failover).

## 0.1.102

- **DHCP relay: operator no longer needs to configure `dhcp-relay-ipv4`
  on the upstream iface separately** (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.187).  RtrDhcpRelay
  now runs `ip route get <server-address>` per unique upstream server
  and auto-adds the resulting egress iface as a synthetic `-i` binding
  on dhcrelay.  Background: ISC dhcrelay's UDP socket is `SO_BINDTODEVICE`-
  filtered per `-i`, so a two-arm relay configured only on the LAN side
  forwarded client DISCOVERs but never saw the server's OFFER reply
  (arrived through the upstream iface that wasn't in the bound list).
  Pre-0.1.102 workaround: explicitly add a second `dhcp-relay-ipv4`
  block on the upstream iface.

Bundles xcespserver 0.1.27, xcespcli 0.1.25, xcespproc 0.1.49,
xcespwdog 0.1.1, xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.187.

## 0.1.101

- **Fix: `copy sw <url> backup-sw` silently failed to update backup-sw**
  (xcespserver 0.1.27).  The async streaming download landed the tarball
  in `$DSK_DIR/img/` but never ran the install step that extracts it
  into `$XCESP_BASE/backupsw/` — the sync copy path did this inline but
  the async one was missing the call.  CLI showed `starting transfer
  ... -> img/...` and returned silently; `show server` kept reporting
  the previous BackupSW version.  Now `finalizeCopyAsync` calls
  `installToBackupSw()` after the download succeeds and surfaces its
  result to the operator.

Bundles xcespserver 0.1.27, xcespcli 0.1.25, xcespproc 0.1.48,
xcespwdog 0.1.1, xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.186.

## 0.1.100

- **Fix: DHCP relay (`dhcrelay`) didn't get restarted after dying on
  its first launch** (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.186 / xcespproc 0.1.48).
  Common path: iface not ready when dhcrelay launched → dhcrelay logs
  "No such device" + "exiting" → supervisor's `isRunning()` got a
  false positive because dhcrelay's dead PID had been recycled by
  another short-lived xcespproc child (ip / sysctl / etc.) →
  supervisor saw "alive" and never relaunched.  isRunning() now
  verifies `/proc/<pid>/comm` is "dhcrelay" before believing the
  signal-based liveness check.

Bundles xcespserver 0.1.26, xcespcli 0.1.25, xcespproc 0.1.48,
xcespwdog 0.1.1, xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.186.

## 0.1.99

- **Critical fix: per-namespace sysctl writes were silently failing
  with `permission denied`** (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.185 / xcespproc 0.1.47).
  Affected `net.ipv4.ip_forward`, `net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding`,
  `net.mpls.platform_labels`, `net.mpls.conf.<dev>.input`, and the
  neighbour GC thresholds (`gc_thresh1/2/3`).  Most topologies kept
  working because the sysctls had already been written as root by an
  earlier boot's xcesp-activate, but fresh Fedora namespaces reliably
  hit it — symptom: DHCP relay test where the central server's
  OFFER/ACK reached the relay router but the relay router couldn't
  forward back to the client because `ip_forward=0` in its namespace.

Bundles xcespserver 0.1.26, xcespcli 0.1.25, xcespproc 0.1.47,
xcespwdog 0.1.1, xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.185.  Same xcesp-ip / xcesp-dhclient
-script as 0.1.97.

## 0.1.98

Feature batch:

- **DHCP server relay-served remote subnets** (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.184) — a
  single `dhcp-server-ipv4` block can now serve its local subnet
  AND/OR any number of subnets reached via dhcrelay.  Schema:
  new `dhcp-server-remote-subnet <prefix>` child carrying
  `dhcp-remote-pool` (required) + `dhcp-remote-gateway` /
  `lease-time` / `dhcp-remote-dns` (optional).  `dhcp-server-pool`
  is now optional (server can be remote-only).  Validator enforces
  "at least one of local pool or remote subnet" and that each remote
  pool/gateway lies inside its declared prefix.
- **`snat-interface` attribute on `nat-snat`** — alternative to
  `snat-address`, mutually exclusive.  RtrNatSnatPObj polls the named
  iface's first IPv4/IPv6 (family per the rule's match-src-address)
  every tick and re-applies the SNAT rule when the address changes
  (e.g. DHCP renew).
- **Unmanaged device kept up on stop** — RtrInterfacePObj::remove() now
  skips the link-set-down AND the address-flush-to-empty when the iface
  is in the default namespace + default VRF and has
  `unmanaged-address true`.  Stopping/restarting xcesp no longer knocks
  the host's external-managed primary NIC offline.
- **`show dhcp-server [router R] [vrf V]`** (xcespcli 0.1.25) — one row
  per pool (local + each remote-subnet) and one row per active lease,
  with VRF filter.

Bundles xcespserver 0.1.26, xcespcli 0.1.25, xcespproc 0.1.46,
xcespwdog 0.1.1, xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.184.  Same xcesp-ip wrapper and
xcesp-dhclient-script as 0.1.97 (no DHCP-client-side changes here).

## 0.1.97

- Ship a tiny privileged wrapper at `/usr/lib/xcesp/xcesp-ip` (compiled C,
  ~30 lines) with file caps `cap_net_admin,cap_net_raw=ep` applied by
  xcesp-activate.  The wrapper raises ambient caps and re-execs
  `/usr/bin/ip`, so xcesp-dhclient-script's `ip addr add` works even when
  ISC dhclient drops the script to a non-root uid with no caps (the
  default behavior on Debian/Fedora — observed at BOUND with CapInh=0
  and uid=xcesp).  Path is intentionally OFF the regular PATH so normal
  users on the box don't gain any privileges; only our script's code path
  benefits.
- xcesp-dhclient-script: route address operations through `$IP` (set to
  the wrapper if present, else plain `ip` — preserves the ARM64-Ubuntu
  path where `/usr/bin/ip` already ships with the right caps and the
  wrapper is therefore unnecessary).
- xcesp-activate: setcap on the wrapper (non-destructive) and SELinux
  fcontext rule labeling it `ifconfig_exec_t` (so Fedora's dhcpc_t domain
  can exec it and the resulting process gets the cap_net_admin policy
  allow rules `ifconfig_t` already has).
- install.sh: deploy the wrapper to `/usr/lib/xcesp/xcesp-ip` AND
  `$MAINSW_DIR/lib/xcesp/` (the latter for CLI self-update consistency
  with management scripts).
- makefile / arm64/build.sh / arm64/package.sh: compile the wrapper
  per-architecture (host gcc for x86, in-Docker gcc for aarch64) and
  bundle it in the matching tarball.
- Same C++ binaries as 0.1.96 (xcespproc 0.1.45 / xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.183).

## 0.1.96

- xcesp-activate: make dhclient setuid root (and strip its file caps) instead
  of granting it file caps.  Same charon-style pattern from 0.1.72.  When
  xcespproc (running as xcesp uid) execs dhclient, the setuid bit elevates to
  root; dhclient's fork-exec of `xcesp-dhclient-script` then runs as root too,
  so `/sbin/ip addr` calls don't depend on file caps on `ip` (Debian ships ip
  cap-less).  Non-destructive: only acts when caps are present or setuid bit
  is missing, leaves stable installs alone.
- xcesp-activate: SELinux fcontext rule + restorecon for
  `/usr/bin/xcesp-dhclient-script` → `dhcpc_exec_t`.  Without this, Fedora's
  dhcpc_t SELinux domain denies the exec silently (targeted policy
  dontaudit's that class of denial).  Falls back to `chcon` if semanage isn't
  installed.
- xcesp-activate: `mkdir -p /var/lib/dhcp` so dhclient's lease file dir
  exists on minimal images that don't ship the isc-dhcp-client package's
  default tree.
- Bundles xcespproc 0.1.45 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.183), which moves the dhclient
  pid/lease paths to `/run/dhclient-xcesp-*.pid` and
  `/var/lib/dhcp/dhclient-xcesp-*.leases` — paths the upstream apparmor
  profile already permits.

## 0.1.95

- xcesp-activate: `apply_apparmor_local` now injects
  `/usr/bin/xcesp-dhclient-script rUx,` into the dhclient profile's local
  override (`/etc/apparmor.d/local/<profile>`).  Without this rule, AppArmor
  on Debian/Ubuntu denies dhclient's `execv()` of the script we ship via
  `-sf`; dhclient logs "bound" on DHCPACK but the script never runs, so the
  iface never gets an IP.  `rUx` = read + unconfined-execute, so the script
  (and its `/sbin/ip` calls) run without AppArmor confinement.  Empty extras
  for any other binary, so the rule is only added where applicable.
- Same binaries as 0.1.94 (xcespproc 0.1.44, xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.182).

## 0.1.94

- Ships `/usr/bin/xcesp-dhclient-script`: a minimal POSIX callback script
  for ISC dhclient.  Only manages the iface address (via `/sbin/ip`); does
  not touch `/etc/resolv.conf`, the default route, hostname, NIS, or NTP —
  those are xcesp's job at higher layers.  Skips the ARPCHECK step (which
  was causing DHCPDECLINE loops on Debian) and avoids dependencies on
  `arping`, `ipcalc`, or `vtysh` (which the dnfv ARM64 Ubuntu
  `/sbin/dhclient-script` requires and silently fails without).
- Bundles xcespproc 0.1.44 (which carries xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.182), which
  passes `-sf /usr/bin/xcesp-dhclient-script` to dhclient.
- install.sh: deploys the new script to `/usr/bin/` AND
  `$MAINSW_DIR/scripts/` so CLI self-update can refresh it on upgrades.

## 0.1.93

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.26, xcespcli 0.1.24, xcespproc 0.1.43,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1.  Carries xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.181 (revert of the
  dhclient `-sf` flag) — DHCP works on Fedora, Debian and Ubuntu
  again.
- **`xcesp-activate` setcap loops are now non-destructive.**  Each
  loop checks `getcap "$bin"` first and only writes file caps when
  the binary currently has NONE.  Distros that ship caps tuned for
  their package (Fedora's dhcp-client, Debian Bookworm's
  isc-dhcp-client) keep their working setup; distros that don't
  (Ubuntu's stock packages) get our baseline.  This applies to all
  daemons in the loops: wpa_supplicant, hostapd, dhclient, dhcrelay,
  dnsmasq, kea-dhcp6.
- Rationale: 0.1.92 unconditionally set
  `cap_net_bind_service,cap_net_raw,cap_net_admin=ep` on every DHCP
  daemon, which on Fedora and Debian *replaced* the package-shipped
  caps with a strict subset and broke DHCP on install.
- `xcesp-dhclient-script` is no longer bundled.  RtrDhcpClient in
  xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.181 doesn't reference it.  `install.sh` removes
  any leftover copy from 0.1.92 so a partial upgrade doesn't leave
  the file in `$BINDIR` or `$MAINSW_DIR/scripts/`.

## 0.1.92

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.26, xcespcli 0.1.24, xcespproc 0.1.42,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1.
- **New management script `xcesp-dhclient-script`** — installed to
  `/usr/bin/` (and `$MAINSW_DIR/scripts/` for CLI self-upgrade).
  Minimal POSIX shell, no Bash dependencies.  RtrDhcpClient passes
  `-sf` to dhclient so our per-netns instances use this script instead
  of the distro's `/sbin/dhclient-script`.  Handles BOUND/RENEW/REBIND/
  REBOOT (ip addr replace + default route), EXPIRE/FAIL/RELEASE/STOP
  (ip addr del), and returns 0 unconditionally for ARPCHECK/ARPSEND
  (the pre-launch flush in 0.0.179 already guarantees a clean iface).
  Does NOT source `/etc/dhcp/dhclient-exit-hooks` or scan
  `/etc/dhcp/dhclient-{enter,exit}-hooks.d/` — third-party hooks on the
  default namespace stay intact.
- **xcesp-activate setcap extended** — dhclient, dhcrelay, dnsmasq,
  and kea-dhcp6 binaries get `cap_net_bind_service,cap_net_raw,
  cap_net_admin=ep`.  Same loop pattern as the existing
  wpa_supplicant/hostapd block.  Fixes silent-fail on Ubuntu where
  the upstream packages ship without file caps, leaving dhclient with
  "Operation not permitted" on the LPF socket and dnsmasq with
  "failed to bind DHCP server socket: Permission denied".  Idempotent
  and additive; doesn't change Fedora behaviour.

## 0.1.91

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.26, xcespcli 0.1.24, xcespproc 0.1.41,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1.  Carries the DHCP client ARPCHECK-loop fix
  (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.179) and the `show interfaces` double-row fix
  (xcespproc 0.1.41).
- **xcesp-activate AppArmor: auto-detect the profile filename by
  binary path.**  The 0.1.90 helper hardcoded `sbin.dhclient`,
  which matches Fedora but not Debian (where the file is
  `usr.sbin.dhclient`).  The helper silently no-op'd on Debian and
  dhclient kept hitting `Permission denied` on its lease/PID files.
  `apply_apparmor_local()` now takes the binary path
  (`/usr/sbin/dhclient`) and finds the profile file by globbing
  `/etc/apparmor.d/*<basename>*` then grepping for the basename to
  confirm.  Adding more daemons later is a one-liner:
  `apply_apparmor_local /usr/sbin/dnsmasq`, etc.

## 0.1.90

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.26, xcespcli 0.1.24, xcespproc 0.1.40,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1.  Carries the daemon-supervisor launch-race fix
  (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.178) and the schema-driven singleton-delete fix
  in xcespcli 0.1.24.
- **xcesp-activate: AppArmor local override for dhclient.**  Drops
  `/etc/apparmor.d/local/sbin.dhclient` extending the upstream
  Debian profile with `/var/lib/xcesp/** rwk,` and `/run/xcesp/**
  rwk,` allowances, then `apparmor_parser -r`'s the profile.  Closes
  the silent-fail mode where dhclient logged `Permission denied` on
  the per-iface PID and lease files, breaking the supervisor.
  Idempotent — content-compared before each write, only rewritten
  on diff.  Helper function `apply_apparmor_local` factored out so
  other daemons (dnsmasq, kea-dhcp6, hostapd, …) can be added as
  they hit similar issues.

