## 0.1.88

- **xcesp-activate**: setcap `cap_net_admin,cap_net_raw=ep` on every
  wpa_supplicant and hostapd binary found under standard paths.
  Needed by xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.176's `RtrDot1xSupPObj` (and the upcoming
  authenticator PObj) when launched inside a named netns via
  `ip netns exec` — file caps on the final binary survive the exec
  chain, where the ambient set otherwise gets washed (cf. the NAT
  capability-wipe lesson from xcespproc 0.1.6).
- `/run/wpa_supplicant` is created at activate-time (mode 0755) so
  wpa_supplicant's default ctrl_interface path exists from boot.
- Bumps xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.175 → 0.0.176, xcespproc 0.1.37 → 0.1.38.

## 0.1.87

- **DHCP feature** (see xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.172).  install.sh creates
  persisted lease dirs under `/var/lib/xcesp/dhcp-client`,
  `/var/lib/xcesp/dhcp4`, `/var/lib/xcesp/dhcp6` (mode 0750, owned by
  xcesp).  `xcesp-activate` pre-creates the matching tmpfs runtime
  dirs under `/run/xcesp/dhcp{-client,-relay,4,6}` on every boot.
  No file capabilities are added — the new daemons (dhclient,
  dhcrelay, dnsmasq DHCP-only, kea-dhcp6) inherit ambient
  capabilities from xcespproc via `IpCmd::launch`.
  Closing hint lists the recommended package installs per distro.

## 0.1.86

- **Hotfix for 0.1.85**: chronyd died with `Fatal error : Not
  superuser` because it does a `geteuid()==0` startup check.
  Fixes:
  - xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.171 / xcespproc 0.1.36: chronyd is now
    launched with `-U` to bypass the root check.
  - **install.sh**: `cap_sys_time` added to the xcespproc
    capability set (`XCESPPROC_CAPS`) so chronyd inherits the
    ability to actually adjust the kernel clock when `settime
    true` is configured.  Without this, settime=true configs
    would silently fail to slew/step the clock.  Reinstalling
    or rerunning `setcap` on the xcespproc binary is required
    after upgrade.

## 0.1.85

- **Hotfix for 0.1.84**: chronyd died at exec with "invalid option
  -- 'g'" because RtrNtpPObj was passing `-g <group>` (a flag that
  exists in dnsmasq but NOT in chronyd — chronyd takes only `-u`
  and uses the user's primary GID).  Fixed in xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.170
  / xcespproc 0.1.35.
- All 0.1.84 installations should upgrade.

## 0.1.84

- **New NTP feature** (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.169 / xcespproc 0.1.34 /
  xcespcli 0.1.22):
  - `router/ntp` configuration section: prioritized upstream NTP
    sources (IP or FQDN), optional NTP server mode for LAN
    clients (bound per-interface), `settime` switch to enable
    multi-router-on-one-box testing without clock contention,
    `version` (3 or 4) and `port` per source.
  - Per-router chronyd, launched in each router's netns with
    --user/--group set to xcespproc's user (same priv-drop fix we
    learned from dnsmasq), cmd socket bound to netns-local
    127.0.0.1:323.
  - `show ntp status [router R]` — chronyc tracking + sources
    parsed and pretty-rendered (offsets in s/ms/µs as appropriate,
    state column maps `*/+/-/?/x/~` to `selected/combine/not
    used/unreach/falseticker/stale`).

## 0.1.83

- `dnsquery` UX fixes (xcespcli 0.1.21 + xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.168 +
  xcespproc 0.1.33):
  - Parser now accepts keyword pairs in any order; if NAME is
    forgotten, prints `NAME (DNS name to resolve) is required`
    instead of silently treating the first arg as the name.
  - Dig wait extended to 12s so dnsmasq has time to return SERVFAIL
    on isolated networks where upstreams are unreachable
    (otherwise dig prints a misleading "communications error ...
    timed out").

## 0.1.82

- **Hotfix for 0.1.81**: dnsmasq's `--user`/`--group` only accept
  user/group NAMES, not numeric IDs.  Look up the current user's
  name via `getpwuid(geteuid())` and pass that instead.  Fixed in
  xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.167 / xcespproc 0.1.32.
- All 0.1.81 installations should upgrade.

## 0.1.81

- **Hotfix for 0.1.80 dnsmasq config-parse failure** ("bad option
  at line 9").  RtrDnsPObj emitted `log-file=<path>` but dnsmasq
  has no `log-file` option — it uses `log-facility=<path>` with a
  path argument.  Fixed in xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.166 / xcespproc 0.1.31.
- The 0.0.165 diagnostic infrastructure (--test pre-flight + stderr
  capture + replay) worked exactly as designed and pinpointed the
  exact line of the problem.

## 0.1.80

- **Hotfix for 0.1.79 dnsmasq respawn loop.**  On routers without an
  explicit `interface lo` block, `dns` configured, the new RtrDnsPObj
  launched dnsmasq every 10 s without it ever staying up.  Three
  fixes shipped in xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.165 / xcespproc 0.1.30:
  - Bring `lo` up in the router namespace before launching dnsmasq
    (required for bind-interfaces + listen-address=127.0.0.1).
  - Pass `--user=<euid>` / `--group=<egid>` so dnsmasq stays as the
    xcespproc user (the default privilege drop to `nobody` could not
    write the pid-file under /run/xcesp/dns/<ns>/, which is 0755
    owned by xcesp).
  - Redirect dnsmasq's stderr to `/run/xcesp/dns/<ns>/dnsmasq.startup.log`
    and replay on every respawn into xcesp.log at WARNING level —
    operators now see the actual error message in the log without
    having to SSH into the box.
- Also adds a `dnsmasq --test -C <conf>` pre-flight to catch syntax
  errors / missing files synchronously before the real launch.
- All 0.1.79 installations should upgrade.

## 0.1.79

- Rebuilds with xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.164 / xcespproc 0.1.29 /
  xcespcli 0.1.20.  Adds:
  - New `unmanaged-address` boolean on device-type interfaces.
    When true, xcesp must NOT add/remove IPs on this interface
    (external manager owns the address list); `shutdown` still
    drives link state.  Validator rejects the flag combined with
    any `address` child block AND on pseudo-device types.
  - New operator commands `show dns [router R]` and `show dns
    statistics [router R]` — first renders dnsmasq state (running
    pid, source binding, upstream priority order, listening
    addresses + proxy interfaces); second triggers SIGUSR1 on
    dnsmasq and parses the per-namespace log for cache counters
    and per-upstream sent/failed totals.
  - Per-namespace dnsmasq log-file emission so the statistics
    command has a stable place to tail.

## 0.1.78

- **Hotfix for 0.1.77**: rebuilds with xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.163 /
  xcespproc 0.1.28.  Fixes a node-type collision where the new DNS
  feature's `server` child node silently overrode the wdog
  top-level `server` schema, making xcespserver crash-loop with
  `top-level node 'router' encountered while block 'l2tp' is still
  open` and never create `/run/xcesp/ctrl.sock` — leaving xcespcli
  unable to connect.  CLI syntax change: the keyword inside the
  `dns` block is now `dns-server <ip>` instead of `server <ip>`.
- All 0.1.77 installations should upgrade.  No config migration
  needed unless an operator had already written a `dns` block with
  the old `server <ip>` keyword (rename to `dns-server <ip>`).

## 0.1.77

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.25, xcespcli 0.1.19, xcespproc 0.1.27,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 with xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.162 and xcespconfig 0.1.2.
- **New `router/dns` configuration section**: per-router `dnsmasq`
  with prioritized upstream server list, optional DNS proxy on
  flagged interfaces, source-address / source-interface egress
  binding, and automatic `/etc/resolv.conf` redirect to `127.0.0.1`
  when the `default` router has DNS configured (original backed up
  and restored on shutdown).
- **New `dnsquery` operator command**: tests DNS resolution from
  inside a specific router's namespace via the streaming action
  protocol; uses `dig` with a `getent` fallback for embedded images
  that don't ship bind-utils.
- Bundles the phy-managed feature wave (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.159–0.0.161)
  and canonical-ordering serialization (xcespconfig 0.1.2 /
  xcespserver 0.1.25 / xcespcli 0.1.17–0.1.18).

## 0.1.76

- Rolls forward to xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.161: phy-managed DDMI polling
  cadence relaxed from every monitor tick (~5 s) to every 6 monitor
  ticks (~30 s).  Same readings, ~6× less fork+exec / I²C churn on
  hosts with many SFP ports.

## 0.1.75

- Rolls forward to xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.160: **SFP DDMI optical readings
  now work on Ubuntu 22.04 / ethtool 5.16 hosts**.  Previously
  `show physical interface <name>` on a FIBRE port displayed only SFP
  identity (vendor / PN / SN) because Ubuntu's ethtool refuses to
  decode the A2 DDM page into text output.  xcespproc now reads the
  raw 512-byte EEPROM via `ethtool -m <dev> hex on` and decodes the
  optical readings (Rx/Tx dBm, temperature, voltage, bias) per SFF-8472
  on the C++ side.  No-op on Fedora 41+ / Ubuntu 24.04+ (newer ethtool
  decodes natively).

## 0.1.74

- Rolls forward to xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.159, xcespcli 0.1.18, xcespproc
  0.1.26, xcesptest 0.1.45: **physical-port management**.  Opt-in
  via `phy-managed true` on an interface of type=device.  Operator
  controls speed/duplex/autoneg via a new `ethernet { … }` sub-block;
  status pipeline carries kernel-reported speed/duplex/autoneg plus
  SFP identity + DDMI optical readings for FIBRE ports.  New CLI
  command `show physical interface <name>` renders all of it.  Kernel
  rejection of an ethtool-s setting is logged + surfaced in
  `show physical` rather than rolling back the commit.
- `install.sh`: post-install summary now recommends installing
  `ethtool` if any phy-managed interfaces are planned.  No package
  manager invocation (matches existing precedent).

## 0.1.73

- Rolls forward to xcespconfig 0.1.2, xcespcli 0.1.17, xcespserver
  0.1.25, xcesptest 0.1.44: **canonical config display**.  `show
  running`, `show candidate`, and the on-disk `xcespserver.conf` now
  emit children grouped by nodeType and naturally sorted by instance
  at every level of the hierarchy.  Mixed-order operator input no
  longer leaks through to readback.

## 0.1.72

- `scripts/xcesp-activate` and `install.sh`: switch charon from file
  caps to **setuid root**, and strip any leftover file caps from
  previous installs.  Reason: Ubuntu's strongSwan charon ships without
  libcap, so its `capabilities_t::keep()` falls through to a
  `geteuid()==0 ? TRUE : FALSE` fallback.  Running charon as `xcesp`
  with file caps grants the caps in /proc/<pid>/status but the check
  ignores them, returns FALSE, and socket-default refuses to register
  ("socket-default plugin requires CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE capability");
  IKE_SAs stay CONNECTING forever.  Setuid root makes charon's euid 0
  inside the per-ns mount/net namespace; the libcap-less fallback then
  passes and socket-default binds 500/4500.  Verified end-to-end with
  RA(x86 Debian)↔RB(ARM64 Ubuntu): IKE_SA HUB established, CHILD_SA
  TUN with AES_GCM_16_128, MOBIKE working.

## 0.1.71

- `scripts/xcesp-activate` and `install.sh`: relax DAC on
  `/etc/strongswan.d/charon/*.conf` (and the Fedora equivalent
  `/etc/strongswan/strongswan.d/charon/*.conf`) by chmod'ing them
  world-readable.  Ubuntu's strongswan-charon ships these files mode
  0600 root:root.  Our per-namespace charon runs as `xcesp`, so the
  glob include in charon-ns.conf finds the files but fails to open
  them — and Ubuntu's strongSwan treats an unreadable include match
  as fatal during init, before syslog opens (identical symptom to
  the empty-glob case fixed in 0.1.70: charon vanishes silently).
  The files contain only plugin enable/disable defaults — no secrets
  — so widening read is safe.  Re-applied on every activate so an
  `apt upgrade` that re-tightens perms is self-healed at next start.

## 0.1.70

- xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.158: `RtrStrongswanPObj::writeStrongswanConf` now
  probes the strongSwan per-plugin enabler dir at write time and emits
  `include <dir>/*.conf` only for directories that actually exist and
  contain `.conf` files.  Required because Ubuntu's strongSwan fatals
  on a glob include with zero matches (exit 66, charon never logs).
  The per-namespace charon-ns.conf is now fully self-contained — no
  bootstrap file, no host-file include, no DAC bypass.
- `scripts/xcesp-activate`: stop generating `/var/xcesp/strongswan.conf`
  (no longer used by xcespproc 0.0.158+) and clean up any stale copy
  from earlier installs.

## 0.1.69

- Trim the per-ns charon bootstrap (`/var/xcesp/strongswan.conf` written
  by `xcesp-activate`) down to the bare minimum: just `load_modular = yes`
  and the per-plugin enabler include.  0.1.68's version pulled in
  `/etc/strongswan.d/*.conf` at the top level — that directory contains
  files for **other** strongSwan components (`charon-systemd.conf`,
  `starter.conf`, `swanctl.conf`) whose settings conflict with our
  plain per-namespace charon (systemd-only logging knobs, ipsec_starter
  PID-file expectations, etc.).  Importing them made charon die silently
  during init on Ubuntu arm64 — same exec-vanishes signature as the
  cap_dac_read_search regression, different cause.
- No xcesp-on-rtr or binary changes — pure shell-script fix.  Bundles
  xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.157 unchanged.

## 0.1.68

- **Revert `cap_dac_read_search` on charon.**  Adding it in 0.1.67 made
  charon's exec die silently on Ubuntu arm64 — no log lines, no
  AppArmor deny in dmesg, no kernel oops, just a vanished process.
  The cap interaction wasn't fully characterised but the symptom
  reproduces deterministically: revert the cap and exec works again.
  Charon caps revert to the original
  `cap_net_admin,cap_net_raw,cap_net_bind_service=ep`.
- **New: per-namespace charon bootstrap file.**  `xcesp-activate` now
  writes `/var/xcesp/strongswan.conf` (mode 0644, owned by xcesp)
  containing the same plugin-loading structure as the system
  `/etc/strongswan.conf` but with absolute include paths.  Generated
  on every boot.  xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.157's `RtrStrongswanPObj` includes
  this file from each per-namespace `charon-ns.conf`, sidestepping
  Ubuntu's locked-down `/etc/strongswan.conf` (mode 0600 owned by
  __ipsec) entirely.  Per-namespace charon now reads a config it owns
  and can always open, the plugin set comes from the absolute-path
  includes pointing at world-readable `*.conf` files in the system's
  `strongswan.d/charon/`, and IKE_SA_INIT actually leaves the box.
- Bundles xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.157.

## 0.1.67

- `install.sh` and `scripts/xcesp-activate`: probe **`/usr/libexec/ipsec/`**
  and **`/usr/lib/ipsec/`** in addition to the existing
  `/usr/libexec/strongswan/` and `/usr/lib/strongswan/` paths when applying
  file capabilities to charon.  Ubuntu's `strongswan-charon` package puts
  the daemon under `/usr/libexec/ipsec/charon` — our older probe missed it
  entirely, so the binary stayed cap-less and our per-namespace charon
  silently failed to load any plugins.
- Add **`cap_dac_read_search`** to the charon capability set.  On Ubuntu
  `/etc/strongswan.conf` ships mode 0600 owned by `__ipsec:__ipsec`; the
  per-namespace charon runs as the unprivileged `xcesp` user, so without
  this cap the `include /etc/strongswan.conf` directive that 0.1.66 added
  to `charon-ns.conf` silently fails the DAC check.  Result: no plugins
  load, IKE_SA_INIT dies with `[NET] no socket implementation
  registered` and 0 bytes leave the box.  With cap_dac_read_search,
  charon can read the system config regardless of its mode, the include
  chain expands (load_modular + per-plugin enablers), and IKE flows.
- The fix is idempotent — install.sh applies it once at install time,
  xcesp-activate re-applies it on every boot (via the systemd
  ExecStartPre=+ hook) in case a strongSwan package upgrade replaces
  the binary and drops its caps.

## 0.1.66

- Per-namespace charon now inherits the system `strongswan.conf` wholesale,
  then adds three overrides (vici socket path, stroke off, bypass-lan
  off).  0.1.65's load_modular+include approach worked on Fedora but
  broke on Debian arm64 where critical plugins (`nonce`, `sha1`) aren't
  enumerated in `strongswan.d/charon/*.conf` — charon refused to start
  with `failed to load 3 critical plugin features`.  Bundles
  xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.156.

## 0.1.65

- Per-namespace charon now loads its socket plugin on distros without a
  compile-time default plugin set (Debian arm64).  xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.155
  generates a `charon-ns.conf` with `load_modular = yes` plus an
  `include` of the system per-plugin .conf directory (both
  /etc/strongswan/strongswan.d/charon/ and /etc/strongswan.d/charon/).
  Without this fix the per-ns charon came up — VICI worked, `show ipsec
  sa` returned data — but `[NET] sending failed: no socket
  implementation registered` blocked every IKE_SA_INIT.  Bundles
  xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.155.

## 0.1.64

- IGP redistribute UX: `static` and `kernel` are now operator-visible
  aliases in OSPFv2, OSPFv3, RIPv2 and RIPng — same fix that has been
  in place for BGP since 0.0.140.  xcespproc installs operator-typed
  `static-route` entries directly into the Linux routing table
  (bypassing FRR's `staticd`), so FRR sees them as `kernel` routes.
  Without the translation `redistribute static` under an IGP was
  silently a no-op.  Bundles xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.154; no other component
  versions changed.

## 0.1.63

- **Route-based IPsec (XFRM interface) tunnel mode.**  Third IPsec data-plane
  mode alongside the existing transport and tunnel-policy modes.  Creates
  a Linux XFRM netdev (kernel ≥4.19) joined to a strongSwan SA via a
  deterministic if-id; packets routed through the device get
  ESP-encapsulated by the SA.  Operator surface:
  ```
  interface tun-hub
    type xfrm
    xfrm
      ipsec-conn HUB
    !
    address 10.99.0.1/30
  !
  ipsec
    connection HUB
      ...
  ```
  Both ends use the same `ipsec-conn` name; the mapper hashes that name
  to allocate a matching if-id on both sides.  Operators who need
  asymmetric or peer-interop control can set `if-id` on the xfrm block
  and `if-id-in`/`if-id-out` on the children explicitly.  Co-exists with
  X.509 (Ch06) and PSK (Ch03/Ch05) on the same router
- Per-namespace `charon-ns.conf` now disables the `bypass-lan` plugin
  (mirrors the host's `load = no` in
  /etc/strongswan/strongswan.d/charon/bypass-lan.conf).  Without this,
  per-namespace charon auto-installed catch-all PASS shunt policies for
  every local subnet, which preempted wildcard-TS SAs used by route-
  based IPsec
- `swanctl --load-all` now runs with `SWANCTL_DIR` set even in the
  default namespace.  Previously the host-side `swanctl` reload
  defaulted to the distro template directory
  (`/etc/strongswan/swanctl/conf.d/` on Fedora) and silently skipped
  loading the connections xcespproc had just written
- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.24, xcespcli 0.1.16, xcespproc 0.1.25,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1, xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.153, xcesp-on-pw 0.0.2,
  xcesp-on-xc 0.0.2, xcespmap 0.1.1, xcespschema 0.1.1,
  xcespconfig 0.1.1, xcesppy 0.0.4

## 0.1.62

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.23, xcespcli 0.1.16, xcespproc 0.1.24,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.149).  Three big security
  features ship together:
  - **Encrypted IPsec PSKs at rest.**  Plaintext PSKs typed into
    `ipsec / secret <NAME> / secret <plaintext>` are replaced on
    commit with `${enc:v1:<base64>}`.  `show running` and saved
    `xcespserver.conf` now contain only the encrypted form.
    Reversible AES-256-CBC + PBKDF2 keyed off `/etc/machine-id`
    (device-bound; restoring a backup to a different machine
    forces the operator to re-enter — see notes).
  - **X.509 certificate management.**  New CLI verbs:
    `certificate ca-import / import / delete / generate-key /
    generate-csr`, `show certificate`.  PEM blobs are pasted via a
    heredoc input mode (sentinel = `END`).  Material lives in
    `/var/xcesp/dsk/cert/{ca,dev,key}/` with restricted perms
    (`0750` dirs, `0640` files, `root:xcesp`).
  - **IPsec X.509 auth.**  Two new schema attrs:
    `ipsec-local.cert <NAME>` and `ipsec-remote.ca-cert
    <NAME>[,<NAME>...]`.  Mapper auto-emits `auth = pubkey`,
    `certs = /…/dev/<NAME>.pem`, `cacerts = /…/ca/<NAME>.pem`, and
    a `private-<NAME> { file = /…/key/<NAME>.key }` stanza so
    `swanctl --load-all` picks up everything in one shot.
- `install.sh` provisions `dsk/cert/{ca,dev,key}` on fresh installs.
  Pre-0.1.62 upgrades need a one-time manual create (or a re-run of
  install.sh).

## 0.1.61

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.22, xcespcli 0.1.15, xcespproc 0.1.23,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.148).  `arp-table-size` moved
  from VRF to router level — the Linux neighbour cache is one-per-
  netns, not per-VRF, so the previous placement was misleading.
- **Migration note**: configs using `router/<R>/vrf/<V>/arp-table-size
  <N>` will be rejected with "unknown attribute 'arp-table-size'" on
  the next commit.  Move the attribute one level up to
  `router/<R>/arp-table-size <N>` and re-commit.

## 0.1.60

- Doc-httpd not starting after install (production-only bug).  Root
  cause: in xcesppkg, the wdog process list at
  `/run/xcesp/xcespwdog_proc.ini` is generated by **xcesp-activate**
  (bash, run via systemd `ExecStartPre=+`), not by xcespserver's C++
  `WdogConfigWriter`.  The 0.1.57 doc-httpd emission landed only in
  the C++ writer that xcesptest consumes — production never saw it.
- Fix in `xcesp-activate`:
  1. Read `[DOC_HTTPD]` from `xcespserver.ini` (POSIX-portable awk
     parser; tolerates `; ... ` and `# ...` inline comments).
  2. When `ENABLED=true` and `DOC_DIR` exists, append a
     `[process.N+1]` block to `xcespwdog_proc.ini` launching
     `python3 -m http.server --bind <addr> --directory <dir> <port>`
     with heartbeat polling disabled and respawn on.
  3. Idempotently inject the `[DOC_HTTPD]` defaults stanza into an
     existing `xcespserver.ini` that predates the feature (same
     pattern as the older `PROC_CONFIG_FILE` injection), so the
     operator can see and edit the tunables in the usual place.
- The on-disk xcesp-activate script self-refreshes from
  `/var/xcesp/mainsw/scripts/` on every service start, so once 0.1.60
  is installed the new logic takes effect at the next
  `systemctl restart xcesp` — no manual edit required.
- Bundled binaries unchanged from 0.1.59 (xcespserver 0.1.22,
  xcespcli 0.1.15, xcespproc 0.1.22, xcespwdog 0.1.1,
  xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.147).

## 0.1.59

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.22, xcespcli 0.1.15, xcespproc 0.1.22,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.147).  CLI fix: `show status` /
  `show running` / `show event` returned nothing when the CLI was
  navigated into a deep path (~30 chars or longer).  Cause was the
  prompt-display path truncation leaking into the server query body;
  introduced a separate `currentFullPathStr()` helper for protocol
  bodies and pointed all six show-command call sites at it.  Pure
  client-side; the on-device xcespserver / xcespproc binaries can stay
  on 0.1.22 / 0.0.147.

## 0.1.58

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.22, xcespcli 0.1.14, xcespproc 0.1.22,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.147).  Adds the per-interface
  `mtu <N>` attribute (integer 68..12000, clamp-and-warn against the
  device's kernel-reported max/min).  Applies to every interface type.
  `show status` reflects the **actual** kernel MTU — the value after
  any clamp — under `router/<rtr>/vrf/<vrf>/interface/<name>/mtu`.

## 0.1.57

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.22, xcespcli 0.1.14, xcespproc 0.1.21,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.146).  Adds a built-in user-manual
  HTTP server, supervised by xcespwdog:
  - The mkdocs-built static site (`doc/site/`) is bundled into the
    package under `doc/` and installed to `/var/xcesp/doc/`.
  - `cfg/xcespserver.ini` gains a `[DOC_HTTPD]` section
    (`ENABLED=true`, `BIND_ADDR=0.0.0.0`, `PORT=8080`,
    `DOC_DIR=/var/xcesp/doc`).
  - xcespserver emits an extra `[process.N]` block into
    `xcespwdog_gen.ini` so xcespwdog launches and respawns
    `python3 -m http.server` autonomously.  The docs stay up while
    xcespserver restarts.
  - Bundling is conditional: if the build host's `../doc/site/` is
    absent the doc tree is skipped (package still builds; the
    `[DOC_HTTPD]` block is a no-op when DOC_DIR is empty).
  - **Note on default bind**: `0.0.0.0` is intentional for the INI-only
    phase.  A future schema-driven `doc-server` block will flip the
    default to `127.0.0.1` and make LAN exposure an explicit opt-in.

## 0.1.56

- Bundles xcespserver 0.1.21, xcespcli 0.1.14, xcespproc 0.1.21,
  xcespwdog 0.1.1 (xcesp-on-rtr 0.0.146).  New `traceroute` CLI
  command:
  ```
  traceroute ADDRESS [source ADDR] [router ROUTER] [vrf VRF]
             [max-hops N] [protocol udp|tcp|icmp] [port N]
  ```
  Mirrors `ping`: same CLI_ACTION_EXEC wire path, same PTY streaming
  back to the operator, same ambient-CAP_NET_RAW delegation in the
  forked child.  `-n` (no-DNS) is hardcoded in the wrapper.  VRF
  binding uses `-i <vrf-master>`, source via `-s`.

